Case reference number AU-RPL-20-00056 is a clinical trial case initially received
from Australia on 05-Oct-2020, referring to a 93-year old white male subject with
cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) who experienced *severe left anterior
descending (LAD) disease and severe aortic stenosis*. The subject 102-6102-0004,
was enrolled in RPL-002-18: A randomized, controlled, Open-Label, Phase 2 Study
of Cemiplimab as Single Agent in Combination with RP1 in Patients with advanced
cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma.
In addition to cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, the subject's relevant medical
history included hypertension, gout and bradycardia. The subject's concomitant
medications included oral Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid), 100 mg daily since
2009, for hypertension, oral Progut (allopurinol), 300 mg daily since 2009, for
gout, oral Noten (atenolol), 25 mg daily since 30-Jun-2020, for hypertension and

datastring.name: Describe Reaction Conitnued__extended
datastring.dstemplatestring:
bradycardia, oral Endone (oxycodone hydrochloride), 2.5 mg as required since 02-Aug-2020, for pre dressing
change prophylaxis and intravenous (IV) sodium chloride 0.9 %, STAT, once on 22-Sep-2020, for renal impairment
hydration post computerized tomography (CT) contrast.

On 30-Jun-2020, the subject initiated treatment with intratumoral RP1 ((rHSV-1 hGM-CSF/GALV-GPR-)),
administered at a dose of 1 x 10%6 PFU/ml, per protocol (total volume 1.5 mL). On 21-Jul-2020, the subject
initiated treatment with intravenous (IV) cemiplimab, administered at a dose of 350 mg, as combination therapy
with RP1l. On 22-Sep-2020, the subject received the last dose of RP1, administered at a dose of 1 x 10%*7 PFU/ml1
(total volume 1 mL) with cemiplimab, at a dose of 350 mg prior to the event onset.

On 02-Oct-2020 (approximately 8 days after study treatment), the subject was presented to Emergency Department
(ED) with shortness of breath (SOB) on exertion *related to severe LAD disease and severe aortic stenosis*. He
was admitted to the hospital for further investigation. Investigations that were performed that day were Chest
X-ray revealed right lobar atelectasis, biochemistry showed grade I renal impairment, haematology and cardiac
laboratory were not clinically significant and COVID-19 virus test was negative.

On 03-Oct-2020, CT pulmonary angiogram was performed and revealed new bilateral lower zone ground-glass
infiltrates. There was no pulmonary embolus. Treatment medications included; oral indapamide, 1.5 mg daily,
oral atenolol, 50 mg daily, furosemide, 20 mg daily, IV ceftriaxone, 2 g daily and IV azithromycin, 500 mg
daily.

On 06-Oct-2020, the subject was discharged from the hospital and the *events* were resolved with sequelae (to
be clarified).

*On 30-Oct-2020, angiogram was performed and severe LAD disease and severe aortic stenosis was diagnosed.
Severe LAD disease was treated with drug-eluting stent, twice’.

Action taken with RP1 and cemiplimab due to the events was reported as 'dosage maintained’.

The Investigator assessed the events of *severe LAD disease and severe aortic stenosis*, both as a grade 2
(moderate) and *not related* to RP1 and cemiplimab. Alternative aetiology was not reported.

All follow-up information is blended into the case narrative above, with the latest information presented
between asterisks (*).

Follow-up information received from the study site on 08-Oct-2020:

Event outcome and resolution date updated.

Follow-up information received from the study site on 05-Nov-2020:

Event term updated to reflect final diagnosis. SOB confirmed to be a symptom of final diagnosis. Pneumonia or
pneumonitis were removed as differential diagnoses, as well as infection versus immunotherapy related
pneumonitis. Causality assessments for the events of severe LAD disease and severe aortic stenosis were
reported as not related to cemiplimab; therefore, the case was not considered as a SUSAR anymore.

both events not related to RP1 and cemiplimab.
